subsubsection.p:
Remember that a linear function requires two pieces of information- a starting value (b, the y-intercept), and an amount of incremental change in the independent variable (m, the slope of the function). This gives us three ways to describe a linear function:
Verbally: A function with a constant rate of change
Graphically: Lines can look like one of four cases:
A line with positive slope, passing through the origin
\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ axis x line = middle, axis y line = middle, every axis y label/.style={at={(ticklabel cs:1.1)}}, y label style={at={(axis description cs:.5,1.1)},anchor=north}, ylabel = {$y$}, every axis x label/.style={at ={(ticklabel cs:1)}}, x label style={at={(axis description cs:1.1,.5)},anchor=east}, xlabel = {$x$}, xmin=-1,xmax=1, xtick = \empty, ytick = \empty ] \addplot[thick,smooth,domain = -1:1] {x}; \end{axis} \end{tikzpicture}
A line with negative slope, passing through the origin
\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ axis x line = middle, axis y line = middle, every axis y label/.style={at={(ticklabel cs:1.1)}}, y label style={at={(axis description cs:.5,1.1)},anchor=north}, ylabel = {$y$}, every axis x label/.style={at ={(ticklabel cs:1)}}, x label style={at={(axis description cs:1.1,.5)},anchor=east}, xlabel = {$x$}, xmin=-1,xmax=1, xtick = \empty, ytick = \empty ] \addplot[thick,smooth,domain = -1:1] {-1*x}; \end{axis} \end{tikzpicture}
A line with slope 0 (horizontal line)
\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ axis x line = middle, axis y line = middle, every axis y label/.style={at={(ticklabel cs:1.1)}}, y label style={at={(axis description cs:.5,1.1)},anchor=north}, ylabel = {$y$}, every axis x label/.style={at ={(ticklabel cs:1)}}, x label style={at={(axis description cs:1.1,0)},anchor=east}, xlabel = {$x$}, xmin=-1,xmax=1, xtick = \empty, ytick = \empty ] \addplot[thick,smooth,domain = -1:1] {.5}; \end{axis} \end{tikzpicture}
A line with undefined slope (vertical line)
\begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ axis x line = middle, axis y line = middle, every axis y label/.style={at={(ticklabel cs:1.1)}}, y label style={at={(axis description cs:.5,1.1)},anchor=north}, ylabel = {$y$}, every axis x label/.style={at ={(ticklabel cs:1)}}, x label style={at={(axis description cs:1.1,.5)},anchor=east}, xlabel = {$x$}, xmin=-1,xmax=1, xtick = \empty, ytick = \empty ] \coordinate (a) at (.5,-1); \coordinate (b) at (.5,1); \addplot[domain = -1:1] {0}; \end{axis} \draw[thick] (a)--(b); \end{tikzpicture}
Algebraically: f(x) = mx+b

